hazard analysis system for slac personnel page 1 area hazard analysis work form title bldg 131 smb sample prep lab location bldg & rm 131 209 instructions an area hazard analysis aha is a process that is used to evaluate a work area to 1 determine the hazards that may be present 2 determine appropriate controls for these hazards and 3 provide a mechanism to communicate these hazards to someone entering the area the aha covers the facility and equipment within the facility it does not cover specific jobs tasks that may be performed in the area job task specific hazards and controls are covered by the jham process the aha should be done by the area manager in cooperation with the building manager an aha should be done once for all working areas and whenever there is a change in to the facility or regulations or the introduction of new equipment or new hazard complete instructions and supporting information is available at https www internal slac stanford edu esh slacsafety jham aha_instruction htm enter information into boxes which will expand to accommodate whatever length of text is entered once this aha is complete the area responsible person signs processes equipment in area hazards recommended controls & actions lab instrumentation centrifuges hot plates furnace uv lamp vacuum pumps glove boxes freezers ultrasonic cleaners low speed diamond saw etc personal exposure via point of operation moving and or cutting parts heat transfer on items that may get hot during operation uv hazards from lamp sources insure lab instrumentation is in good condition before use report any damaged equipment to lab manager label hot plates when in use make sure centrifuges are properly balanced and inspect rotors before use observe safety locks to prevent uv radiation exposure observe posted signs ppe uv protective eyewear when using uv lamps protective gloves for high or low temperature work compressed gasses personal exposure via compressed nitrogen other compressed gasses compressed gas bottles to be stored upright and secured properly at all times cylinders in use must always be fitted with a regulator must be capped if not in use all compressed air and gas equipment to be kept in good condition replace worn gas lines loose fittings etc hazardous materials and chemicals personal exposure via solvents acetone alcohol etc acids and bases other hazardous chemicals training required for working with hazardous materials hazcom and introduction to waste management be aware of the hazards associated with each chemical and practice safe chemical handling storage and disposal page 2 possible burn skin eye injury toxic carcinogen exposure read and observe all msds's waste to be disposed of through slac hazardous waste group containers and samples to be labeled as required all stock quantities to be stored in appropriate cabinets and lockers ppe protective eyewear gloves lab coats close toe shoes as required for level hazard be aware of the location of eye washes and safety showers sharps and breakable items personal exposure via sharp surfaces exposure punctures cuts potential explosive hazards check condition of breakable and sharp items before use report any damaged items to lab manager do not heat closed containers pay attention to task and surroundings ppe protective eyewear and gloves as required for level hazard use appropriate labeled containers for sharps glass disposal cryogenics personal exposure to liquid nitrogen burns eye injury oxygen deficiency ppe use safety glasses gloves long pant and close toe shoes cold rooms hypothermia suffocation wear warm clothing leave cold room when cold post warning limit liquid nitrogen use post limits on door limit compressed gas use post limits on door signs other hazards respect all warning caution signs contact lab manager for review of shop policy and procedures spills personal and environmental hazard resulting from unintentional release of chemicals or other hazardous materials call 9 911 for emergency or major spills contact waste management for minor spills spill kits are available for minor spills use appropriate ppe page 3 other please report other hazards not on this list to the lab manager completed by print name date area responsible cynthia patty 01 aug 2008 participants
